title: For Sale:  Sig P229 Legion - As New
postcontent: Essentially brand new Sig P229 Legion.  I purchased new in May and have shot 3 clips (45 rds.) at one trip to the range and cleaned it thoroughly afterwards.  It is a great shooter and the best gun that I have ever held (I have owned Glocks, CZ's, S&W, Walther, Ruger and other Sigs).  The Grayguns trigger is much better than the standard P229 and M11-A1, and has a very short audible reset.  Double action is still relatively heavy (but better than most) but consistent and smooth. The single action feels very light and smooth.  The slide glides along the rails very smoothly.  The Sig X-ray sights are also a big improvement over the regular night sights, especially the front sight.  The checkering on the front and back straps is aggressive, as are the really good G-10 grips, all of which combine to give you a great handle on the gun with zero slippage, unlike the regular rubber 229 grips.I have owned it just a few months and must sell due to an unexpected financial situation.  The package includes the original case which has instructions, papers, stickers and lock, plus the thermal case shipped from Sig when I registered the firearm which includes the 229 Legion coin and room for the gun and mag, plus the 2 additional mags and cut-out for a knife or flashlight.The price is firm at $900 and I am not interested in a trade.  I will sell only to an Alabama resident, and can ship to your reputable FFL dealer in Alabama if you pay shipping (approximately $40 if through a shipmygun.com preferred FFL, or near $100 if shipped through UPS, the only other alternative).  I can meet you within a reasonable distance of Montgomery, AL to make the exchange.  If interested, text me at REDACTED, or email here through Armslist.

title: For Sale:  Nagant M1895 Revolver
postcontent: For sale I have my Nagant M1895 revolver - manufactured in 1925. The gun has a numbers matching frame, trigger guard, and cylinder, and may also have a numbers matching barrerl, but I don't know much about these guns and can't find a serial number anywhere (the barrel may not even be a serialized part?). Anyway, the gun is in good condition for a surplus firearm, and has had exactly 29 rounds shot through it by me - not sure about any Russians that may have shot this before, but the bore looks good. I also have the original cleaning rod and holster - which kind of smells funny, but what did you expect.The gun itself is pretty dang cool. It's got the cylinder that actually moves forward to seal in the gasses when you pull the hammer back - which makes it one of the few revolvers that you can suppress. Not that you probably would since a suppressor tax stamp literally costs as much as the entire gun, but I digress. It's single/double action, but you probably won't be shooting it double action since the double action trigger pull is not exactly what you would call "light". But hey, it's a surplus gun, not a Colt. It was actually suprisingly accurate from what I saw in my limited shooting, and is a really unique shooting experience. The only reason I'm selling it is because I want to fund some work on my car... I need less expensive passions.I'm asking $270 for the gun and 71 rounds of ammunition (two boxes of 50 rounds, one of which is missing the aforementioned 29 rounds). Thanks for looking and have a great day!

title: For Sale:  Femaru Model 37M
postcontent: I WANT TO MOVE THIS PISTOL OUT AND INTO THE HANDS OF A COLLECTOR OR SOMEONE WHO WILL APPRECIATE IT!I am selling my very rare and collectible 1941 FEMARU-FEGYVER-ES GEPGYAR R.T. 37M otherwise known as a Hungarian Femaru Model 37M.I paid $275 for ths pistol at an estate sale plus $125 for an original magazine as the pistol only came with an aftermarket magazine (which I would include).  The seller and myself knew nothing about this pistol and after doing extensive research, found out it's true value.If you were to look at Gunbroker.com, GunsAmerica.com. the Blue Book or many on-line dealers, you would see these go for anywhere between $350-$600+ depending on condition.  The original magazines alone cost between $100-$200 now.  This pistol is now a fully authenticated 1941 Femaru 37M with the addition of the original magazine.The magazine is probably going to need a new spring as the seller told me he broke off about 1"of the spring when he was restoring it.  I would probably take the spring out of the aftermarket magazine and install it in the original magazine.  As a note, in 1941 mags had no matching serial numbers or any serial numbers at all.I am a shooter, not a collector and I shoot regularly at the range.  After finding out the value of this pistol, I do not take this to the range anymore.  Naturally, it has been test fired and broken down and cleaned & oiled extensively.  It is remarkably accurate given it's fixed sights.I own a host of pistols and do not need this lying around.  I put the condition of this pistol on the high side of 'good' and am mainly looking to get back out of this what I have put into it.The pistol was designed by Frommer, a prominent Hungarian gun manufacturer in Budapest, Hungary and produced weapons for the Hungarian Army.  In 1929 Frommer originally produced the 29M which was superceded in 1937 by the 37M.  It is styled after the proven design of the Colt 1911 as most manufacturers did and still do.This 1941 37M is 'pre-war' and not to be confused with weapons produced during the Nazi occupation.  There are NO Nazi markings on this pistol.  When Nazi Germany occupied Hungary and took over the Frommer facility, they re-named the Femaru 37M 'Pistole 37(u)', the lower case (u) was used to signify it's Hungarian origin.As you can see from the photo's showing the serial # and the dates of manufacture, this pistole is 80 years old.  The caliber is .380acp and was referred to as 9mm Kurz(European).The .380 barrel and magazine are interchangeable with the 7.65 (.32acp) which Frommer produced for the German Luftwaffe after Nazi occupation and were made to be equipped with an additional safety at the rear of the slide.  The only safety on an origianl Femaru 37M such as this is a grip safety.I could go on and on about the history of the manufacturer, etc., but my space is limited.  I also have many more photo's, but I'm only allowed 3 here.  If you need further info, more photo's, a specific photo or more intense documentation, you can contact me through 'Contact the seller' at the top of the page.I am located in Srping Hill, FL.I am asking $400 firm, cashiers check only.  No CC's.  I do not want trades.  Receipt will be issued.  You would be responsible for all shipping and any related costs.(NOTE:  AT TOP OF LISTING IT SHOWS SHIP AS "NO'.  I DON'T KNOW HOW TO MAKE IT 'YES'.)  I do not ship to California!
